<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-04-18T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-04-18T14:00:00-05:00" n="878" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d878">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00 Bandit Activities, 1931/52:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Vice Consul at Bluefields</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Rowe</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-04-18T14:00:00-05:00">April 18, 1931—2
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>Your April 17, 6 p.m., third paragraph. The Naval vessels now on duty at
                            Puerto Cabezas, Bluefields, and Cape Gracias a Dios will remain until
                            the present difficulty is over.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>